## Log

2026-07-15  Scaffolded. No work started.

2026-07-16  source done. The primary is unusually strong for this repo: the MODBUS Application
            Protocol Specification V1.1b3 is free, needs no login, and is served by the publisher
            (modbus.org) itself. It publishes worked examples IN LITERAL HEX BYTES, per function
            code, so the answer key is the wire.
            Two independent readers each fetched the publisher's own PDF (sha256 f80d0d71...,
            932,519 bytes), each rendered the pages at 3x, and read the tables as images. They agreed
            on every byte of all five examples (pattern 12).
            ⚠ INSTRUMENT NOTE: `curl -sIL` returns 404 on every real modbus.org PDF URL. The server
            404s on HEAD and serves 200 application/pdf on GET for the SAME url. Both readers hit it
            independently. A HEAD based link check concludes the whole spec library is dead.

2026-07-16  learn done, and the finding is a quote rather than an opinion: MODBUS TCP IS A SERIAL
            PROTOCOL WEARING A TCP HEADER. The PDU is capped at 253 bytes because of "the size
            constraint inherited from the first MODBUS implementation on Serial Line network (max.
            RS485 ADU = 256 bytes)" (APP 4.1 p5), and MBAP spends one of its four fields on a Unit
            Identifier defined as "Identification of a remote slave connected on a serial line or on
            other buses" (TCP 3.1.3 p5).
            This route matters: RS-232, RS-485 and HSMS were all checked for a project of their own
            and ALL SIX relevant standards are paywalled (TIA-232-F $165, TIA-485-A $99, SEMI E37
            $380; $1,324 for the set, no free normative access, SEMI's abstracts state no normative
            content). Rule 9 forbids claiming conformance to an unread standard, so none of them can
            anchor a verified project. RS-485's fingerprint is reachable anyway, for free, because
            Modbus documents it ON ITSELF.
            Also settled: TIA-485-A would not even answer a biasing question. Its own published scope
            says it "does not specify other characteristics, such as signal quality, timing,
            protocol, pin assignments".

2026-07-16  build + verify done. 79 checks, 31 mutants, all dead, gate green.
            Built: spec.js (published constants, each with its page + the five frame answer key),
            engine.js (CRC, PDU encode/decode, published validation order, RTU and MBAP transports,
            the refusal), verify/verify.js, hand rolled UI with no dependencies.

            THE PRECISE CLAIM, because the sloppy version is FALSE and shipping it would have been an
            overclaimed gap of the same family as the plan's old "zero hours" scorecard:
              ❌ "Modbus does not define byte order."  APP 4.2 p5 defines it explicitly, big endian.
              ✅ Modbus defines byte order WITHIN a register and defines NO data type wider than a
                 register, so there is no published word order to follow. Measured across all three
                 specs, 265,402 chars, controls firing 176 to 538 times: float 0, floating 0,
                 ieee 754 0, 32-bit 0, word order 0, byte order 0, 40001 0, 4x 0.
            ⇒ Section F: decodeWide() throws without a named vendor profile, and VENDOR_PROFILES is
            EMPTY on purpose. Same law as 03's "there is no THE ATS", reached from a third direction.
            Four mutants break no calculation at all and only make the tool overclaim. All die.

            🔴 A UI BUG NO SUITE COULD SEE, AND THE SECOND TIME THIS REPO HAS HIT THIS CLASS.
            The Read Coils REQUEST and RESPONSE are BOTH five bytes, so a length based label guesser
            put the request's field names on the published response: CD 6B 05 rendered as an address
            and a quantity when APP 6.1 p12 calls them a byte count and coil status. Every byte was
            correct. Nothing threw, nothing overflowed, the node suite was green AND the browser
            structural check was green, because both compare BYTES and this was a lie told in WORDS,
            on a tool built to teach which byte is which. Only an eye caught it, exactly like 03's
            emergency lane reading "failed" at t=0. fieldLabels() now lives in engine.js, REQUIRES a
            direction rather than guessing it, and six checks plus two mutants pin it.

            GAP, recorded rather than papered over: the CRC algorithm is NOT verified against a
            published message to CRC pair. The procedure (preload FFFF, polynomial 0xA001) and the
            byte order (Fig 30: 0x1241 goes out 41 12) are published and asserted; a worked
            message to CRC example was not found. Deliberately NOT closed with a value from a
            tutorial (pattern 20). The fix when someone has budget: SERIAL pp40-42 publish a
            reference C implementation with two 256 entry tables. Transcribe them AT THE PUBLISHER
            and check the bitwise procedure reproduces all 512 values. That is 02's shape exactly.

            SCOPE, stated because the slug oversells it: NO METER REGISTER MAP IS SOURCED. The spec
            defines none, because a meter's map is its vendor's. This ships the FRAME layer only.
            Naming the project "modbus-meter" does not entitle it to invent a meter.
